## Features
- **Register / login / logout** via Flask-Login sessions.
- **Per-user notes CRUD** (title + body); the list query is scoped to `owner_id = current_user.id`, so you only ever see your own notes.
- **SQLite** auto-created on first run.

## How each mandatory security requirement is met
| Requirement | Implementation |
|---|---|
| SQL injection | Every query uses `?` bound parameters — no string building |
| Password hashing | `bcrypt` with per-password salt (`bcrypt.gensalt()`) |
| Input validation | WTForms validators (length, `^[A-Za-z0-9_.-]+$` for usernames, required) |
| XSS / output encoding | Jinja2 context-aware autoescaping + strict CSP (`script-src 'self'`, no inline) |
| CSRF | Flask-WTF token on every POST, including logout and delete buttons |
| Access control / IDOR | `_owned_note_or_404()` scopes edit/delete/fetch by owner; mismatch → 404 |
| Secure session cookies | `HttpOnly`, `SameSite=Lax`, `Secure` (env-configurable) |
| Security headers | CSP, X-Content-Type-Options, X-Frame-Options, Referrer-Policy, Permissions-Policy, HSTS |
| No error/trace leakage | `debug=False` by default; custom 400/403/404/500 handlers with generic messages |
| No hardcoded secrets | `SECRET_KEY` read from env — **app refuses to start without it** |

## To run it locally (port 5028)
```powershell
python -m venv .venv
.\.venv\Scripts\Activate.ps1
pip install -r requirements.txt
$env:SECRET_KEY = "<run: python -c 'import secrets; print(secrets.token_hex(32))'>"
$env:SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE = "false"   # only for local plain-HTTP testing
python app.py
```
Then open http://127.0.0.1:5028.

One design note worth flagging: the session cookie is `Secure` **by default** (the mandatory requirement), but I made it overridable via `SESSION_COOKIE_SECURE=false` so login actually works over plain HTTP on localhost — otherwise the browser would refuse to send the cookie and you couldn't log in during local testing. In production you leave it at the default `true` behind HTTPS.

